document_summary:
The Presidential Records Act of 1978 (Public Law 95-591) amended title 44 of the United States Code to establish the legal framework for the preservation and public availability of presidential records. The act defines presidential records as materials created or received by the president, his immediate staff, or units or individuals in the Executive Office of the President whose function is to advise and assist the president, in the course of conducting activities that relate to or have an effect upon the carrying out of the president's constitutional, statutory, or other official or ceremonial duties. The act requires that presidential records be managed and preserved in a manner that will ensure their availability to the public. The act also establishes restrictions on access to presidential records, including a 12-year duration for restricted access to information classified as national security or foreign policy secrets. The Presidential Records Act (PRA) was enacted in 1978 and amended in 2009. The PRA establishes the legal framework for the management of Presidential records. The Act requires that Presidential records be managed in accordance with the provisions of the Federal Records Act (FRA), with some exceptions. The Act also requires that the Archivist of the United States maintain custody of Presidential records, and that such records be made available to the public under conditions specified in the Act.

The PRA defines "Presidential records" as "documentary materials, or any reasonably segregable portion thereof, created or received by the President, his immediate staff, or a unit or individual of the Executive Office of the President whose function is to advise or assist the President, and which relate to the transaction of public business." The Act exempts certain categories of records from this definition, including records that are subject to executive privilege, records that are personal to the President and not related to public business, and records that are created before January 20, 1981.

The PRA requires that Presidential records be managed in accordance with the provisions of the Federal Records Act (FRA), with some exceptions. The Act exempts Presidential records from the FRA's requirements for disposal of non-record materials and for publication in the Federal Register of descriptions of record series subject to the Act. The PRA also exempts Presidential records from the FRA's prohibition on disclosure of information protected by executive privilege.

The PRA requires that Presidential records be made available to the public under conditions specified in the Act. The Act provides for public access to Presidential records through the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), except to the extent that such records are protected by executive privilege. The PRA also requires that the Archivist of the United States establish procedures for public access to Presidential records that are restricted pursuant to a determination made by the Archivist.

The PRA authorizes the Archivist of the United States to enter into agreements for the deposit of Vice-Presidential records in non-Federal archival repositories. The Act also authorizes the Archivist to enter into agreements for the management of Presidential records held by private entities.
